  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1752813079" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1752813079" />
    <a title="Katherine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13311251-katherine"><img alt="Katherine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577842427p2/13311251.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1752813079?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katherine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katherine" href="/user/show/13311251-katherine">Katherine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=middle-grade">middle-grade</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=school">school</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=contemporary">contemporary</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=books-to-screen">books-to-screen</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=cute-and-fluffy">cute-and-fluffy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=right-in-the-childhood">right-in-the-childhood</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=talk-to-the-animals">talk-to-the-animals</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13311251-katherine?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1752813079" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4808755473164062338"><b>
  <i>”Just about everything that happened to me that summer happened because of Winn-Dixie.”</i>
</b><br/><br/>I’ll admit right here and now that <b>I’m not a dog person.</b> Never have been and never will be. I think Chihuahuas are Satan’s minions, I can’t stand Boston terriers (long story on that one), and I’m extremely terrified of large dogs. I’m such a teeny tiny person and dogs are notorious for being excited to see someone that they tend to charge at you like a bull running down the streets of Seville. And once the</span>
  <span id="freeText4808755473164062338" style="display:none"><b>
  <i>”Just about everything that happened to me that summer happened because of Winn-Dixie.”</i>
</b><br /><br />I’ll admit right here and now that <b>I’m not a dog person.</b> Never have been and never will be. I think Chihuahuas are Satan’s minions, I can’t stand Boston terriers (long story on that one), and I’m extremely terrified of large dogs. I’m such a teeny tiny person and dogs are notorious for being excited to see someone that they tend to charge at you like a bull running down the streets of Seville. And once they decide to run full speed ahead, it’s bye-bye petite little me. I’ve been knocked down more times than I care to admit, and it’s gotten to the point that if I see a big dog running in my general direction, I go and hide behind the closest thing I can find, climb a tree, or run as fast as my short legs can. I’m a cat person through and through, and always will be. I’ll be a little old lady in a pink house stitching and reading while about ninety cats or so run around everywhere. <br /><br />But for one brief shining moment, after first reading this book when I was eight-years-old as my assigned reading in third grade, <b>I wanted a dog like Winn-Dixie.</b><br /><br />The plot is pretty simple; India Buloni goes to the store for some items but doesn’t get said items, cause she finds something much better; a dog.<blockquote>
  <i>”My name is India Opal Buloni, and last summer my daddy, the preacher, sent me to the store for a box of macaroni-and-cheese, some white rice, and two tomatoes and I came back with a dog.”</i>
</blockquote>Consequently, this quote pretty much describes me, but replace ‘dog’ with ‘cat’. <br /><br />This is more of a character and emotion driven novel than one driven by plot. There is no clear objective or goal for the characters in mind. There’s no lost treasure to be found or mystery to be solved. Rather, this novel focuses on the little things in life, such as human emotions and friendship. <b>It’s about letting go of things lost and facing demons we’re too ashamed to admit we have.</b><blockquote>
  <i>”I lay there and thought how life was like a Littmus Lozenge, how the sweet and the sad were all mixed up together and how hard it was to separate them out.”</i>
</blockquote>It’s about forming new friendships and starting over, and realizing that all promises aren’t meant to be kept.<blockquote>
  <i>”’When I told you your mama took everything with her, I forgot one thing, one very important thing she left behind.’<br />‘What?’<br />‘You. Thank God your mama left me you.’”</i>
</blockquote>In meeting characters such as Opal, the preacher, Gloria Dump, Franny Block, Otis, Sweetie Pie, the Dewberry brothers, and Amanda Wilkinson, we learn about their quirks, their trials, and their triumphs, and <b>how a certain dog named Winn-Dixie manages to bring out the best in them</b> and bring these extremely different people together in the most surprising of circumstances.<br /><br />This short but sweet little book is much like Winn-Dixie himself; not much to look at from the outside, but with its gentle sense of humor and big heart, will quickly find a place in your own heart, as well as your bookshelf. In harkening back to children’s classics featuring animals such as <i>Charlotte’s Web</i>, <i>Mrs. Frisby and the Rats of Nimh</i>, and <i>Shiloh</i>, this instant classic in the making depicts <b>not only how one dog brings joy not just to the human he found, but to the entire town.</b></span>
  <a data-text-id="4808755473164062338" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

